Problem 1: Processing Text and Making Word Clouds (35 points)

In Lab3 (a long time ago) we worked with a dataset containing tweets (from Twitter) about airlines, but we never looked at the text data! Now, in our last lab, we’re going to revisit that dataset and look at the text. Here’s the dataset:

library(tidyverse)
airline_tweets <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/zjbranson/315Fall2021/main/TweetsSimplified.csv")

Since you probably don’t remember this dataset from Lab3 (I think it would be bizarre if you did): This dataset contains information about Tweets made about airlines. Most of these Tweets are made while someone is waiting to board a flight. Here are the variables in this dataset:

  • text: The text of each tweet. This is the main variable we will focus on.
  • airline: The airline that the Tweet was about.
  • airline_sentiment: The estimated sentiment of each tweet, labeled as “positive”, “negative”, or “neutral.” For the sake of this lab, we will take these sentiment labels at face value; we will explore sentiment further in the homework.

  1. (20pts) Now create a separate word cloud for Southwest, American, and jetblue (this is contained in the airline column of the dataset). To do this, follow these steps:
  • Make American, Southwest, and JetBlue datasets by subsetting the airline_tweets dataset. Call these american, southwest, and jetblue.
#subsets for different airlines
american <- filter(airline_tweets, airline == "American")
southwest <- filter(airline_tweets, airline == "Southwest")
jetblue <- filter(airline_tweets, airline == "JetBlue")
  • Similar to Problem 1A, we will preprocess the text from each of these three subsets. To save you time, here’s a function you can use to do some of the preprocessing in Problem 1A:
preprocessText = function(text){
    text = Corpus(VectorSource(text))
    #change to lowercase
    text <- tm_map(text, content_transformer(tolower))
    # Remove punctuations
    text <- tm_map(text, removePunctuation)
    # Eliminate extra white spaces
    text <- tm_map(text, stripWhitespace)
    return(text)
}

Then, using this function, write code that defines preprocessed text for the three airlines; call these american.text, southwest.text, and jetblue.text.

american.text = preprocessText(american$text)
southwest.text = preprocessText(southwest$text)
jetblue.text = preprocessText(jetblue$text)

Please also set each word cloud to a different color, such that it is easier to differentiate each word cloud. The above code requires you to have defined american.text and jetblue.text, which you should have defined in Part A. Then, the following code creates a Term-Document matrix using the function TermDocumentMatrix(), with TF-IDF weights:

tdm_both <- TermDocumentMatrix(tweetsAmericanJetBlue, control = list(weighting = weightTfIdf))

Note that this is a Term-Document matrix; thus, terms are in the rows and documents (tweets) are in the columns!

Then, using the resulting tdm_both, do the following:

  • For each word, compute the total TF-IDF weighting for American. Hint: Use rowSums() on the Term-Document Matrix, but only for the columns corresponding to American (thus, you’ll need to figure out how many documents are in American).   1. (15pts) As a review of old material, let’s consider which airlines tend to get different kinds of sentiment, at least in terms of their tweets. In particular, answer the following questions:
  • Use a statistical test to assess if the proportion of negative tweets is significantly different across airlines. Note that, for any given airline, the proportion of negative tweets is (1) the total number of tweets such that airline_tweets == "negative" divided by (2) the total number of tweets about that airline. Thus, to answer this question, you can use prop.test(x, n), where x is set to the vector of negative tweets for each airline, and n is set to the vector of total tweets for each airline. (Hint: You can use the table() function to easily get these vectors.) After you write your prop.test() code, be sure to write your formal conclusion from the statistical test.

There are a few ways you could define the vectors of total negative tweets and total tweets; I’ll demonstrate one way just using the table() function. First, note that this is the contingency table for airline and airline_sentiment:

table(airline_tweets$airline, airline_tweets$airline_sentiment)
##                 
##                  negative neutral positive
##   American           1960     463      336
##   JetBlue             955     723      544
##   Southwest          1186     664      570
##   United             2633     697      492
##   US Airways         2263     381      269
##   Virgin America      181     171      152

The first column corresponds to the total numbers of negative tweets, and the row sums correspond to the total numbers of tweets. Thus, we can define the desired vectors in this way:

negativeTweetTotals = table(airline_tweets$airline, airline_tweets$airline_sentiment)[,1]
tweetTotals =  rowSums(table(airline_tweets$airline, airline_tweets$airline_sentiment))

Then, we can run prop.test():

prop.test(x = negativeTweetTotals, n = tweetTotals)
## 
##  6-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity
##  correction
## 
## data:  negativeTweetTotals out of tweetTotals
## X-squared = 1142.4, df = 5, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## sample estimates:
##    prop 1    prop 2    prop 3    prop 4    prop 5    prop 6 
## 0.7104023 0.4297930 0.4900826 0.6889063 0.7768623 0.3591270

We see that the p-value is nearly 0; thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the negative tweet proportions are equal, thereby concluding that they are different.

  • Consider the proportion of (1) negative tweets, (2) positive tweets, and (3) neutral tweets for each airline. Among these three proportions, which airlines have negative tweets as the highest proportion? (In other words, which airlines have a plurality of negative tweets?) After you’ve answered that question: Does this make sense, given the context of the data? (Hint: Remember, most of these Tweets are made while someone is waiting to board a flight.)

There are several ways that you can compute the (1) negative, (2) positive, and (3) neutral proportions for each airline (indeed, we computed the negative proportions in the previous part, and we could repeat the same process for positive and neutral). Instead, we will use the prop.table() function (which we actually saw in our first lab!)

prop.table(table(airline_tweets$airline, airline_tweets$airline_sentiment), margin = 1)
##                 
##                    negative    neutral   positive
##   American       0.71040232 0.16781443 0.12178325
##   JetBlue        0.42979298 0.32538254 0.24482448
##   Southwest      0.49008264 0.27438017 0.23553719
##   United         0.68890633 0.18236525 0.12872841
##   US Airways     0.77686234 0.13079300 0.09234466
##   Virgin America 0.35912698 0.33928571 0.30158730

Note that each row adds up to 1; thus, each row displays the proportion of negative, positive, and neutral tweets for each airline. We can see that all airlines have their plurality of tweets as negative tweets (i.e., in each row, the negative number is higher than the other two numbers). This is unfortunate for the airlines, but it is intuitive: This finding makes sense given the context of the data, because I imagine that most people would have the gumption to tweet about an airline only when they have a complaint about that airline, especially when they are waiting to board a flight.
